{
  "slug": "tapestry-interlocking-weft-joins",
  "title": "Tapestry interlocking weft joins",
  "subtitle": "Linking two weft colours at a vertical boundary without a slit",
  "excerpt": "When two colour areas meet at a vertical line in tapestry weaving, you have a choice: leave a deliberate slit, or link the two wefts together at the boundary. Interlocking and interlinking are the two main ways to do that, each producing a slightly different visual result.",
  "type": "TECHNIQUE",
  "categorySlug": "fibre-arts",
  "subCategorySlug": "weaving",
  "difficulty": "INTERMEDIATE",
  "season": null,
  "sourceType": "PUBLIC_DOMAIN",
  "sourceNotes": "- Hooper, Luther. Hand-Loom Weaving: Plain and Ornamental. Pitman, 1910. Available via Internet Archive. Covers tapestry weft joins and slit vs joined colour-area construction.",
