  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "In tapestry, when two colour areas meet at a vertical line you have a choice: join them, or leave an open "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "slit",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termSlug": "slit-tapestry"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". Slits are used in many traditions, but a long vertical slit weakens the cloth. The two main ways to join, "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "interlocking",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termSlug": "interlocking"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " and "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "interlinking",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termSlug": "interlinking"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", each give a slightly different result at the seam."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "suppliesCard",
        "attrs": {
          "items": [
            "Tapestry loom, warped and ready",
            "Two colours of tapestry weft yarn",
            "Tapestry bobbins or butterflies, one per colour",
            "Tapestry beater or comb",
            "Scissors"
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Understanding the slit join"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "slit-tapestry",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termSlug": "slit-tapestry"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " join happens when both "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "wefts",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termSlug": "weft"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " turn back around the same "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "warp",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termSlug": "warp"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " thread on every row, leaving a literal gap. In Peruvian and Navajo weaving, slits up to about 4 rows long are commonplace and can be sewn closed during finishing. Beyond that length, especially on a wearable piece, the slit weakens the cloth and is better replaced with one of the methods below."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Method 1: interlocking"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "In "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "interlocking",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termSlug": "interlocking"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", each weft loops around the other weft before turning back. No "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "warp",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termSlug": "warp"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " thread sits at the join; instead the two "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "wefts",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termSlug": "weft"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " link in the space between two warp threads."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Step 1: Weave colour A from left to right up to the planned boundary. Leave the bobbin hanging."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Step 2: Weave colour B from right to left up to the same boundary from its side. Leave the bobbin hanging."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Step 3: Bring colour A's bobbin up from below and loop it around colour B's weft before turning colour A back to the left."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Step 4: Turn colour B back to the right."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Step 5: On subsequent rows, always loop colour A around colour B (or B around A) from the same direction. Mixing directions creates a visible ridge; keep it consistent."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Interlocking produces a firm, closed seam. When the join is perfectly vertical and the loop is made consistently, it is nearly invisible from the front. If the loop direction alternates by accident, a raised vertical line appears on the face of the work."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Method 2: interlinking"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "In "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "interlinking",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termSlug": "interlinking"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", each "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "weft",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termSlug": "weft"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " passes through the other colour's open "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "shed",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termSlug": "shed"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " at the boundary before turning back. This creates a slightly looser seam than interlocking, and is more practical when the boundary is not perfectly vertical."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Step 1: Open the shed for the current row. Weave colour A across its section, but before turning, pass the tail of colour A through the last few warp threads of colour B's territory (through the open shed). Then turn colour A back."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Step 2: Weave colour B across its section. Before turning, bring colour B's tail through the open shed in colour A's territory by just 1-2 threads, then turn back."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Step 3: Beat gently. The interlinking loops pull both sections together at the join."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Interlinking works better for diagonal or curved colour boundaries. The two "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "wefts",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termSlug": "weft"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " share a few "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "warp",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termSlug": "warp"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " threads at the join, so the boundary can shift left or right without the join failing."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When to use a lazy line instead"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "lazy line",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termSlug": "lazy-line"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " avoids the join question altogether by making the colour boundary diagonal rather than strictly vertical. Each row, the turning point steps one "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "warp",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termSlug": "warp"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " thread to the left or right, so the two colour areas overlap at the diagonal. The result is no join at all; the colours blend at a soft angle. Lazy lines work well when the colour boundary follows a curved or angled line in the design."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "items": [
            {
              "problem": "A raised ridge appears at the interlocking join",
              "solution": "Check that the loop direction is consistent on every row. If colour A loops around colour B from below on row 1, it must do so on every row. Alternating the direction causes the visible ridge."
            },
            {
              "problem": "A small gap appears even though interlocking is used",
              "solution": "The loop is probably forming in mid-air rather than snugging down between the two warp threads. After looping, tug both bobbins gently outward before beating so the join sits at the warp-to-warp space."
            },
            {
              "problem": "The interlinking join looks messy where one colour overlaps the other",
              "solution": "Reduce the overlap to exactly 1 warp thread on each side. Passing through more than 2 warp threads creates a visible colour bleed at the boundary."
            }
          ]
        }
      }
    ]
  }
}
